message 14: by Bt (new) - rated it 5 stars
Apr 03, 2016 09:20AM

I rated this book 5 stars because I ended up enjoying it immensely and respecting the talents and abilities of Kafka to take the reader through Gregor’s transformation with such a keen attention to details that eventually results in the reader being permitted and encouraged to feel everything that each of the characters were feeling. All of this was somehow accomplished without using any superfluous words - amazing. It is, in my opinion, a really great achievement.

(view spoiler)[
I thought this book was a really well written allegory of what it must feel like to be judged an abomination by people who fear and ultimately end up hating those who are different – be it their ideas, looks, beliefs, religion, nationality, culture… The transformation of Gregor resulted, for me, from some sort of realization by or announcement to his family that he was not in essence what they had allows thought he was or should be. I felt for all of them and saw quite clearly how the ones who inflict their prejudices on others suffer just as much if not more than the ones being judged. In this case, I felt that Gregor was much better able to stay true to his heart and continue to love them even through all of their seeming prosecution and torture. His final act of choosing to die was done in order to release his family from the torment they felt, even if that torment was misguided and because of their misunderstanding of who he was. It was an ultimate act of love and self-sacrifice. This is a book that I feel would release many more gems of understanding to the reader who chooses to spend time rereading it and reflecting on some of the deeper issues and truths that it offers. I will never look at a cockroach in the same light again. (hide spoiler)]

message 21: by Paula W (new) - rated it 4 stars
Apr 07, 2016 08:24AM

I finished this morning and wavered between 3 and 4 stars, finally going with 4. I thought this was really well done. The matter-of-fact tone of the narrator was interesting in a "Suspend all disbelief because this thing happened and it's no big deal so let's just go with it" way. Although Gregor woke up with the body of an insect in the very first line (and nobody really spent any time wondering how or why it happened), it took a while for his thoughts and feelings to become less human-like. I think that focusing on his transformation almost makes one miss the changes the other characters went through. The genius of this short story, in my opinion, is that every character went through a metamorphosis, and perhaps Grete more so than Gregor.

message 27: by Jon (new) - rated it 4 stars
Apr 09, 2016 04:30AM

Cansu wrote: "I like the disconnect between mind and body, and I like how Kafka made the reader feel alienated from the family along with Gregor. But I guess I don't see how this is a great literary work?."

Well one thing literature is meant to do is make you feel things. At a basic level if you were compelled, moved, or made to think then it is at least a 'good' work of literature. I tend to think of 'great' in terms of art being more about how influential it is rather than how much 'analysis' it lends itself too.

But in terms of reading closer: I read it ages ago and remember being most impressed by the weird, almost comic way it plays out with no one ever doubting it is Gregor, no one asking how it happened.

But on rereading it yesterday I was much more interested in the way POV works in relation to the psychology of all the characters. Like he just keeps giving his family love and they repeatedly poop on him even before the transformation.

An illustrative example might be the way day he hides himself under the couch where he can't breath properly so that his appearance doesn't upset his family. He's such a doormat that it is left to the reader to think that maybe as family they might owe him some love too.

Which is all something Kafka couldn't do if everyone didn't just sort of accept the transformation in that surreal way. Like try reading it with the thought that he has woken up hideously disfigured or disabled or sick – rather than as a vermin – and the reactions of the family take on a really different tone.

So I guess the way psychology, form, voice, atmosphere all work in a way that was innovative at the time is why it is 'great'.

Others here may have other views.

reply | flag *

m8: by Phil (new) - rated it 5 stars
Apr 09, 2016 05:06AM

Cansu wrote: "Hello! I just finished this little book! I couldn't decide between 3 and 4 stars, but went with 3. This is mostly because, although I enjoyed it, I didn't really understand some of the main themes ..."

Teachers are great ruiners of books. A teacher once explained Kafka's theme by saying (view spoiler)[ It's about being an artist. Gregor is a burden on his family. He can't connect with them. He's just fundamentally different and his brain is different than theirs. They are only happy when he's out of the sight. Also, "Samsa" is thinly veiled code for "Kafka" and Kafka died in a sanitarium for people with "nervous disorders." (hide spoiler)]This answer fits the story very well, but I think it limits the story unnecessarily and commits the foul of just saying that a person's writing is an inevitable byproduct of their biography. I prefer to see it more broadly in terms of feelings of discomfort in your own skin and uncertainty about your place in the world.

message 33: by Laurie (new) - rated it 4 stars
Apr 11, 2016 04:32AM

Even knowing the basic premise of this story beforehand, I found it rather amazing. It is stark, sad, and grotesque. I expected to be disgusted by Gregor, and I was. Imagining a human-sized insect with lots of small waving legs, a hard-shell back and snapping jaws is nasty. But Kafka did an incredible job making me feel Gregor's humanity that remains hidden inside of him. He wants to talk to his family, and he wants to show up to work and continue to provide for his loved ones. Gregor wants to maintain some semblance of his old life by keeping his furniture in his room even though they are being removed for his comfort. He is still Gregor on the inside.

So it was such a sad ending when he heard his sister deny that he is Gregor. I think he would have died anyway since he was slowly starving, but Gregor died at that time because he gave up hope. His sister, who meant the most to him and had taken care of him the entire time since his transformation, finally denied his humanity. She wants to get rid of him, so his last shred of hope for his old life is gone. It was heartbreaking to me even though I knew death was the only end possible for him.

I kept thinking while reading this that this story would be very different if written today. It was published 101 years ago, and nowhere do you see Gregor ask why this has happened to him. I think that would be one of the primary themes of the story if it were written now. Gregor would be asking why am I an insect? Did I contract a virus, did I breathe in some chemicals, am I part of a scientific experiment that I don't know about, did I anger the gods? Why, why, why? But the question is never asked in Kafka's story, and I found that astounding in a work that is considered a classic of philosophy.

reply | flag *

message 35: by Lisa (new)
Apr 12, 2016 07:42AM

After a trip to Eastern Europe including six days in Prague and several visits to the Trapdoor Theatre in Chicago (which does Eastern European plays), I get "metamorphoses." Many symbols, fairy takes, magic realism, and fantasies are used to express political ideas. If they said what they actually meant, they'd get a one-way ticket to Siberia. Go back and read it again with a grain or maybe a block of salt. You'll like it better.

message 46: by Phil (new) - rated it 5 stars
Apr 15, 2016 10:44AM

Lisa wrote: "After a trip to Eastern Europe including six days in Prague and several visits to the Trapdoor Theatre in Chicago (which does Eastern European plays), I get "metamorphoses." Many symbols, fairy tak..."

I usually think of Kafka's work as intensely personal, like a roadmap of his innermost brain. If you were looking for historical context, though, it ought to be mentioned that he was writing during the WWI era, died in Central Europe in the early 1920s, and that many of his family members died in the Holocaust shortly thereafter. On a personal level, he was stuck in mind-numbing clerking jobs and ended up in a sanitarium by the time of his death. You can see how this environment would breed a sense of paranoia and faceless oppression.

message 50: by Nargus (last edited Apr 16, 2016 04:57AM) (new) - rated it 5 stars
Apr 16, 2016 04:35AM

Wow ... it's amazing how there's so much more to gain from a book than just reading it and having your initial thoughts and ideas about it. Thanks for the perspectives and insights guys! I thought it was an incredible story - hence the five stars, I really loved it - so creative, imaginative, and original. I think you stop focusing on the bizarreness of it after the first sentence, because you're in the mind of a human - who thinks human - in fact, I couldn't help but empathise right away with the nuisances of travel Gregor spoke about.

It's interesting Gregor's priorities differ from everyone else's, and with this juxtaposition of his ideas with everyone else's, Kafka paints a very telling picture of people.

I think it was very sad. Ultimately how his sister feels is very important - there's a connection there that's constantly referred to. Toward the beginning, he counts on his sister bringing him the right food without him indicating it, and says otherwise he'd perish - a foreboding to what ended up happening. She stopped caring - but more than that, she denied his existence.
